1950.

00:12:54.335 --> 00:12:57.636
And I'm just going to walk
through this.

00:12:57.636 --> 00:13:02.376
You only have one in your
handouts, but I'll show you how

00:13:02.376 --> 00:13:05.000
it's moving along.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.490
Moving along,
you can think of this as

00:13:08.490 --> 00:13:12.358
generations moving through the
population.

00:13:12.358 --> 00:13:15.094
And this is the date up here.

00:13:15.094 --> 00:13:19.150
So, this is 1950,
1955, you can see this red

00:13:19.150 --> 00:13:19.811
cohort.

00:13:19.811 --> 00:13:24.622
A cohort is a group of
individuals that were born at

00:13:24.622 --> 00:13:26.698
roughly the same time.

00:13:26.698 --> 00:13:30.188
So, you can see that red cohort
there.

00:13:30.188 --> 00:13:32.830
And we are going along,
1965.

00:13:32.830 --> 00:13:36.037
This lip here,
that we can now see,

00:13:36.037 --> 00:13:40.000
is the postwar baby boom.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.553
That's what I'm a member of.

00:13:42.553 --> 00:13:47.113
If you can see it in this bulge
in this population.

00:13:47.113 --> 00:13:49.666
And now were marching along.

00:13:49.666 --> 00:13:53.861
Here's my cohort,
and I just put these lines on

00:13:53.861 --> 00:13:55.776
to keep you oriented.

00:13:55.776 --> 00:13:57.965
And here comes you guys.

00:13:57.965 --> 00:14:00.883
I think those are you guys,
1985.

00:14:00.883 --> 00:14:05.534
That's roughly right,
because I never know when I've

00:14:05.534 --> 00:14:09.000
last updated these slides.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:10.749
So, and here you go.

00:14:10.749 --> 00:14:15.821
See, here's the big bulge of
all of these baby boomers that

00:14:15.821 --> 00:14:19.494
you guys are going to have to
take care of.

00:14:19.494 --> 00:14:22.642
And now, we can actually see an
echo.

00:14:22.642 --> 00:14:26.140
This is what's called the baby
boom echo.

