And I like to write it that way
because then,

00:38:49.609 --> 00:38:54.506
we know what this looks like,
right?

00:38:54.506 --> 00:38:56.744
Let's plot that.

00:38:56.744 --> 00:39:00.102
This is N and this is T.

00:39:00.102 --> 00:39:05.000
What does that look like?

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:10.666
I know this is really
rudimentary but remember we're

00:39:10.666 --> 00:39:13.666
modeling population growth.

00:39:13.666 --> 00:39:20.333
So here, if we plot the log of
N, and this is what we do with

00:39:20.333 --> 00:39:23.333
cultures of microorganisms.

00:39:23.333 --> 00:39:25.000
That's a flask.

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:30.000
Those are a lot of microbes in
there.

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:36.614
And what we do is we sample it
at various points in time,

00:39:36.614 --> 00:39:43.937
and if you take the log we get
a nice straight line that we can

00:39:43.937 --> 00:39:47.007
draw a regression through.

00:39:47.007 --> 00:39:51.968
And what's the slope of that
line equal to?

00:39:51.968 --> 00:39:52.204
r.

00:39:52.204 --> 00:39:53.149
Exactly.

00:39:53.149 --> 00:40:00.000
The growth rate in the units:
N to the minus one.

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:06.447
OK, what's the Y intercept?

00:40:06.447 --> 00:40:07.164
N0.

00:40:07.164 --> 00:40:20.537
OK, now suppose we want to
calculate the doubling time of

00:40:20.537 --> 00:40:32.000
the population,
the time it takes to double.

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:36.619
How would we do that?

00:40:36.619 --> 00:40:41.460
Let's first define it.

00:40:41.460 --> 00:40:50.260
It's the time,
T, that it takes for NT to

00:40:50.260 --> 00:40:54.440
equal to N0, right?

00:40:54.440 --> 00:41:05.000
If we start with N0 the
population doubles.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:10.750
Then, that's the time at NT.

00:41:10.750 --> 00:41:23.071
So, we want to solve for that T
for the time it takes for the

00:41:23.071 --> 00:41:28.000
population to double.

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:40.616
Since natural log of NT over N0
equals rT, then the natural log

00:41:40.616 --> 00:41:53.029
of, sorry, 2N0 over N0 equals
rT, and T equals the natural log

00:41:53.029 --> 00:42:03.000
of two divided by r equals our
doubling time.

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:07.317
Does that make sense?

00:42:07.317 --> 00:42:17.185
I'll put this out there so you
can see it better.

00:42:17.185 --> 00:42:26.643
What's the natural log of two?
0.69, thank you,

00:42:26.643 --> 00:42:36.100
always a handy thing to have in
our repertoire.

00:42:36.100 --> 00:42:47.202
So, that's just the way,
it's easier to think about the

00:42:47.202 --> 00:42:56.660
time it takes for a population
to double often,

00:42:56.660 --> 00:42:58.926
then the instantaneous growth
rate.

